note: Modern pagination added in pencil, upper outer corners; catchwords every verso, lower left.
Dimensions of original manuscript: 212 x 145 (165 x 95) mm bound to 212 x 160 mm.
Notes and prayers appear on most flyleaves and blank pages in different hands.

msIdentifier.repository: University of Pennsylvania Museum of Archaeology and Anthropology

msContents.summary: Composite manuscript containing 8 works and pages of notations, written in at least three hands. The majority of the works are related to Ḥadīth and other anecdotes related to Muḥammad and other prophets. Some of the paper is machine made; the flyleaves and blank pages have also been covered in notes; some pages have been removed.

persName.#text: Shayẓamī, Mubārak ibn Aḥmad, active approximately 1716

msItem.title: Hādhihi al-qiṣṣah yurīdu bi-hā ṣabī ṣaghīr māta bi-ʻishq wa-shawq ilá Nabīnā
Kitāb fīhi munājāt sayyidinā Mūsá ʻalayhi al-salām

layoutDesc.layout: Written in 15-24 long lines with poetry in two columns.

scriptDesc.scriptNote: Written in maghribī in dark brown and black ink; pointed.

decoNote: Rubrications in red and blue; two simple finispieces in red and green (p. 118, 135); textblock ruled in red and brown (p. 109, 118, 135).

binding.p: Bound in brown leather with flap (Type II); blind-tooled frame with stamped central mandorla and small flower stamps in the interior corners of the frame; coordinating stamp on the flap; plain paper pastedowns; endbands in blue and white chevron pattern.

origin.p: The date 1213 A.H. (1798 or 1799) appears at the end of part 4 (p. 109), and 1189? A.H. (1775 or 1776) appears at the end of part 5 (p. 113). The digits 28 (in Hindu-Arabic numerals) appear at the bottom of p. 135, which could mean that part was copied in 1228 A.H. (1813 C.E.). The scribe gives his name as Mubārak ibn Aḥmad al-Shayẓamī (p. 135).

history.provenance: Acquired during the Expedition in Morocco by Talcott Williams and Sophia Wells Royce Williams, 1898.
